When several tests need the same setup — like a logged-in user — you can define a custom fixture by extending Playwright's `test`:

const test = base.extend({
  loggedInPage: async ({ page }, use) => {
    await page.goto('/login');
    await page.fill('#username', 'demo');
    await page.click('#submit');
    await use(page);
  },
});

Now any test can request `loggedInPage` and start out already authenticated.

A page object is typically a class that takes a `page` in its constructor and exposes methods for the actions a user can take:

class LoginPage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
    this.username = page.locator('#username');
    this.password = page.locator('#password');
    this.submit = page.locator('#submit');
  }
  async login(user, pass) {
    await this.username.fill(user);
    await this.password.fill(pass);
    await this.submit.click();
  }
}

With page objects in place, a test becomes a short, readable sequence of intentions:

test('user can log in', async ({ page }) => {
  const loginPage = new LoginPage(page);
  await loginPage.login('demo', 'pass123');
  await expect(page.locator('.welcome')).toBeVisible();
});

Anyone reading this — even without deep Playwright knowledge — can follow what's being verified.

Playwright lets you build tests in a loop by calling `test()` inside a `forEach`:

const invalidEmails = ['plainaddress', 'missing@dot', '@nodomain.com'];
invalidEmails.forEach(email => {
  test(`rejects invalid email: ${email}`, async ({ page }) => {
    await page.fill('#email', email);
    await page.click('#submit');
    await expect(page.locator('.error')).toBeVisible();
  });
});

This produces three separate, individually reportable tests from one block of code.
